Wash and dry produce.

Dice @tomato{1} into ¼-inch pieces. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Drain @black beans{1%can}.

In a #medium pot{} (use #large pot{} for 4 servings), combine @white rice{1/2%cup}, tomato, garlic, beans, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @Fajita spice blend{1%tsp} (you'll use more later), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{20-22%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Quarter @lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, cilantro, and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4 servings). Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%oz} dry with paper towels and season all over with @Fajita spice blend{1%tsp}, salt, and pepper. (Use the rest of the Fajita spice blend as you like.)

> Swap in pork chops or steak for chicken. Cook chicken until browned and cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side, or cook steak to desired doneness, 5-7 minutes per side.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

> TIP: If chicken starts to brown too quickly, lower the heat and cover pan.

Transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest.

Fluff rice and beans with a #fork{} and stir in @butter{1%tbsp}.

Slice chicken crosswise.

Divide rice and beans and chicken between plates in separate sections. Pour any resting juices over chicken and drizzle with crema. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Slice pork, chicken, or steak against the grain.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.